<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>iron lady • iron maiden</xh5><p> <i>iron lady—</i>1. said of a tough or intransigent woman: She was an <u>iron lady</u> who took part in the rallies even after her head was injured twice in police baton charges. 2. <i>(Iron Lady)</i> the nickname of Margaret Thatcher, British Prime Minister (1979–1991): The <u>Iron Lady</u> of British politics, Margaret Thatcher was the longest continuously serving prime minister since 1827.</p><p><i>iron maiden—</i>1. an old instrument of torture: A person was placed inside the box of the <u>iron maiden</u> while the door (which had impaling spikes on the inside) was closed slowly to maximize pain. 2. <i>(Iron Maiden)</i> = iron lady 2: Tension was exacerbated by the cold-war rhetoric which both President Reagan and Mrs. Thatcher consciously adopted, the latter reveling in the “<u>Iron Maiden</u>” label.</p> </entry>
